{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17658705","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17658705"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T22:53:31+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T22:53:31+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20813"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"20813","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/20813"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.08,0.04,0.21,0.58,0.08]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13688"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"97363"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"13688","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/13688"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20813"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79978"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"10851"},{"type":"tags","id":"11653"},{"type":"tags","id":"12438"},{"type":"tags","id":"12439"},{"type":"tags","id":"12795"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"32966"},{"type":"contributions","id":"32967"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"97363","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/97363"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003ETesting for latent tuberculosis infection can be performed using either tuberculin skin tests or interferon-gamma release assays.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the testing for latent tuberculosis infection?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Positive tuberculin skin tests reliably differentiate between latent infection and active disease","Tuberculin skin tests are more specific than interferon-gamma release assays in BCG-vaccinated individuals","Interferon-gamma release assays detect antibodies against tuberculosis antigens","Interferon-gamma release assays measure T-cell production of interferon-gamma in vitro","False-negative results are uncommon in patients with active tuberculosis disease"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe correct answer is that \u003Cstrong\u003Einterferon-gamma release assays measure T-cell production of interferon-gamma in vitro\u003C/strong\u003E. Interferon-gamma release assays (IGRAs) are blood tests that detect T-cell responses to \u003Cem\u003EMycobacterium tuberculosis\u003C/em\u003E antigens. In these tests, the patient\u0027s lymphocytes are stimulated with specific tuberculosis antigens, and the production of interferon-gamma by T-cells is measured to assess immunity to the organism.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPositive tuberculin skin tests reliably differentiate between latent infection and active disease\u003C/strong\u003E - Neither tuberculin skin tests nor IGRAs can differentiate between latent tuberculosis infection and active tuberculosis disease. They only indicate exposure and immune response to \u003Cem\u003EM. tuberculosis\u003C/em\u003E.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETuberculin skin tests are more specific than interferon-gamma release assays in BCG-vaccinated individuals\u003C/strong\u003E - This is incorrect. Tuberculin skin tests can produce false-positive results in BCG-vaccinated individuals because the purified protein derivative contains antigens that cross-react with BCG. IGRAs are more specific in this population.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInterferon-gamma release assays detect antibodies against tuberculosis antigens\u003C/strong\u003E - IGRAs detect T-cell responses and interferon-gamma production, not antibodies. They measure cell-mediated immunity rather than humoral immunity.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFalse-negative results are uncommon in patients with active tuberculosis disease\u003C/strong\u003E - False-negative results can actually occur in patients with active tuberculosis disease, as well as in those with immunosuppression, malnutrition, certain viral infections, sarcoidosis, and Hodgkin lymphoma.\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe tuberculin skin test involves intracutaneous injection of purified protein derivative of \u003Cem\u003EM. tuberculosis\u003C/em\u003E, which induces a visible and palpable induration that peaks in 48 to 72 hours in sensitised individuals. Both IGRAs and tuberculin skin tests detect T-cell-mediated immunity to mycobacterial antigens but cannot distinguish between latent infection and active disease.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Latent tuberculosis infection is detected by measuring T-cell responses to Mycobacterium tuberculosis antigens using either interferon-gamma release assays or tuberculin skin tests.","Interferon-gamma release assays measure T-cell production of interferon-gamma when stimulated with Mycobacterium tuberculosis antigens in vitro.","The tuberculin skin test can produce false-positive results in people previously vaccinated with BCG or infected with atypical mycobacteria.","Both tuberculin skin tests and interferon-gamma release assays can produce false-negative results in immunocompromised patients or those with active tuberculosis."],"references":["Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Philadelphia: Elsevier; 2020. Chapter 8; page 371."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79978"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20813"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79978","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisio